org.domainobject.animation.sp.arrayobject

Interface _IndexedMemoryFast<T extends ArrayObject>

  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of array object held in memory
    All Superinterfaces:
    _IndexedMemory<T>, _Memory<T>, java.lang.Iterable<T>

    public interface _IndexedMemoryFast<T extends ArrayObject>
extends _IndexedMemory<T>

    A type of indexed memory that indexes array objects the moment you add them. This is what the "fast" part of the name refers to, rather than its speed. Especially if you expect to add a lot of non-unique array objects, this type of memory will take up less application memory than the "lazy" memory variant, because adding a non-unique array object will only result in the index being updated. The array object itself is discarded.

    Contrary to plain (non-indexed) and "lazy" memory, you must call commit on an array object created through the newInstance method. Otherwise it will not be visible to the burn process. Also, a fast memory's object counter (reflected by the size method) will not be updated until you call commit on the array object. You must call commit before you call newInstance or add again. Otherwise the array object will simply be overwritten.

    Author:
    Ayco Holleman

    • Method Detail

      • addUnique

        void addUnique(T arrayObject)
        Add the specified array object under the assumption that it is unique. This saves a hash table lookup to see if an equivalent array object already exists in memory, which might be advantageous for very large memory objects. Only use this method if you know the array object to be distinguishable from all other array objects in memory. Adding non-unique array objects has undefined consequences.

        arrayObject -
